---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '@/components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';

// NOTE: This replaces src/pages/projects/snapdaemon.astro, which was an
// empty file rendering a blank page. The copy below is written from your
// resume's one-liner ("Software based implementation of Wooting Keyboards'
// SnapTap feature") — flesh it out with the real implementation details
// when you have a minute.
---

<Layout
  title="SnapDaemon — case study"
  description="A software implementation of Wooting's SnapTap: last-input-wins key resolution as a background daemon."
>
  <Header />
  <main>
    <article class="cs section">
      <div class="wrap cs__wrap">
        <a class="cs__back" href="/#work" data-cursor-hover>← Back to work</a>

        <header class="cs__head">
          <span class="eyebrow">Case study — 2024</span>
          <h1 class="cs__title">SnapDaemon</h1>
          <p class="cs__lede">
            A software implementation of Wooting keyboards' SnapTap feature — last-input-wins
            key resolution, running as a background daemon on any keyboard.
          </p>

          <dl class="cs__meta">
            <div>
              <dt>Stack</dt>
              <dd>C++ · Linux input events</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Type</dt>
              <dd>System daemon</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Source</dt>
              <dd><a href="https://github.com/arenvista" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-cursor-hover>github.com/arenvista ↗</a></dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </header>

        <section class="cs__section">
          <h2>The problem</h2>
          <p>
            Wooting's SnapTap (a form of SOCD handling) resolves the classic counter-strafe
            conflict: when both <code>A</code> and <code>D</code> are held, the keyboard reports
            only the most recently pressed key instead of both or neither. On Wooting hardware
            it's a firmware feature — SnapDaemon brings the same behavior to ordinary keyboards
            in software.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="cs__section">
          <h2>The approach</h2>
          <p>
            The daemon sits between the physical device and the applications reading from it.
            It watches raw key events for the configured opposing pairs, tracks press order, and
            rewrites the emitted state so the last pressed key always wins — releasing it hands
            control straight back to the still-held opposite key, with no gap where both or
            neither register.
          </p>
          <p>
            Because it operates at the input-event level rather than inside any one game, the
            behavior is universal and the pairs are configurable.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="cs__section">
          <h2>What I took away</h2>
          <p>
            Input handling is a timing problem before it's a logic problem. Getting the
            resolution to feel instant meant treating every event as state to reconcile, not a
            message to forward — the same shift in thinking that shows up in the interfaces I
            build now.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .cs__wrap {
    max-width: 46rem;
  }

  .cs__back {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--teal);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .cs__head {
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  .cs__title {
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    font-size: clamp(2.6rem, 8vw, 4.5rem);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }

  .cs__lede {
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    max-width: 55ch;
  }

  .cs__meta {
    margin: 2.5rem 0 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    padding-block: 1.5rem;
    border-block: 1px solid var(--line);
  }

  .cs__meta dt {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--fg-faint);
  }

  .cs__meta dd {
    margin: 0.35rem 0 0;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--fg-primary);
  }

  .cs__meta a {
    color: var(--teal);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .cs__section {
    margin-top: 3rem;
  }

  .cs__section h2 {
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .cs__section p {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .cs__section p + p {
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
  }

  .cs__section code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    background: var(--paper-deep);
    padding: 0.15em 0.4em;
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-size: 0.9em;
  }
</style>
